<p class="entry-meta">Published: <time class="entry-time">Jan 27, 2014</time> Modified: <time class="entry-modified-time">Sep 3, 2025</time> Author: <span class="entry-author"><a href="https://foragerchef.com/about/" class="entry-author-link" rel="author"><span class="entry-author-name">Alan Bergo</span></a></span></p></header><div class="entry-content"><div class="wprm-recipe wprm-recipe-snippet wprm-recipe-template-snippet-basic-buttons---sans-print"><a href="#recipe" data-recipe="21677" style="color: #ffffff;background-color: #000000;border-color: #333333;border-radius: 3px;padding: 5px 8px;" class="wprm-recipe-jump wprm-recipe-link wprm-jump-to-recipe-shortcode wprm-block-text-normal wprm-recipe-jump-inline-button wprm-recipe-link-inline-button wprm-color-accent"><span class="wprm-recipe-icon wprm-recipe-jump-icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><g class="nc-icon-wrapper" fill="#ffffff"><path data-color="color-2" d="M9,2h6c0.6,0,1-0.4,1-1s-0.4-1-1-1H9C8.4,0,8,0.4,8,1S8.4,2,9,2z"></path> <path fill="#ffffff" d="M16,11V5c0-0.6-0.4-1-1-1H9C8.4,4,8,4.4,8,5v6H1.9L12,23.6L22.1,11H16z"></path></g></svg></span> Jump to Recipe</a>
</div>
<p>There really is no substitute for fresh mushrooms in everyday cooking, but we can get pretty close. Of course they can always be pickled for long term storage, but there's another method, almost in between a pickle and a marinade: the almighty conserve. Think of it as the best pickled mushroom you've ever had.&nbsp;</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img data-perfmatters-preload decoding="async" width="1000" height="713" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-4-of-5.jpg" alt="Chanterelle Mushroom Conserve" data-skip-lazy class="wp-image-15760" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-4-of-5.jpg 1000w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-4-of-5-300x214.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-4-of-5-768x548.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-4-of-5-561x400.jpg 561w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" fetchpriority="high"></figure>
</div>


<p>I used to make 80 lb batches of these pickled mushrooms every week at my first restaurant. It was also sold commercially at Heartland Restaurant and Farm Direct Market in its heyday when we had a market full of preserves like pickles, sauerkraut and other ferments, all made in house.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Real quick for the sticklers: I've seen mushroom <em>"conserva"</em> and <em>"conserve"</em> both on the menus of various restaurants. They're generally going to be the same thing, conserva just being the Italian translation.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image size-full wp-image-30297">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="773" height="1000" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20773%201000'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="A lot of Cantharellus phasmatis a Midwestern golden chanterelle" class="wp-image-30297" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2.jpg 773w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-768x994.jpg 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 773px) 100vw, 773px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="773" height="1000" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2.jpg" alt="A lot of Cantharellus phasmatis a Midwestern golden chanterelle" class="wp-image-30297" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2.jpg 773w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pile-of-Chanterelles-2-768x994.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 773px) 100vw, 773px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Chanterelles are one of the best wild mushrooms for pickling.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-don-t-kill-the-mushrooms-with-vinegar-nbsp">Don't kill the mushrooms with vinegar&nbsp;</h2>



<p>The real magic about this is that it lacks the overkill acidity of most pickling liquids (as well as sugar, which I don't care for in mushroom pickles), but it's still safe enough to can in a water bath.</p>



<p>Kept under their liquid, the pickled mushrooms will stay for a very long time. Some recipes online will say they keep for about a month, let me tell you though, I have kept mushrooms stored like this in restaurants for over a year, having no loss in the quality of the product. Just make sure to keep the pickled mushrooms under their liquid.&nbsp;</p>


<div class="wp-block-image wp-image-5877 size-full">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="700" height="535" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20700%20535'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="hedgehog mushroom conserve recipe" class="wp-image-5877" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11.jpg 700w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11-300x229.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11-523x400.jpg 523w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="700" height="535" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11.jpg" alt="hedgehog mushroom conserve recipe" class="wp-image-5877" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11.jpg 700w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11-300x229.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/hedgehog-mushroom-conserve-11-523x400.jpg 523w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Hedgehog mushrooms are excellent prepared like this too.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-ph-and-canning-safety-nbsp"><strong>PH and Canning Safety&nbsp;</strong></h3>



<p>I don't usually can this in restaurants, since there's walk in coolers, but for home use,you want something shelf stable. I did an experiment to test if this could be canned in 2015, I suspected it could, but I wanted to be 100% sure. Here's the skinny: general standards for pickling and canning say that you want to have a PH under 4.6 or lower for hermetically sealed foods.</p>



<p>Canning food in a pressure canner doesn't require a low PH as the temperature exceeds 242F, which is enough on it's own to ward off botulism. Foods canned in a water bath canner<em> (like this can be)</em> only reach 212F <em>(the boiling point of water)</em>, and that isn't enough on it's own to prevent botulism, so lowering the PH with acid or vinegar is necessary.</p>



<p>To find a sweet spot PH level, I started with 2 cups of liquid and then started adding vinegar, stirring to incorporate, and then testing the PH at 1 and 2 minute intervals to make sure I got a steady reading.</p>



<p>The moral of the story is that mushroom conserve here, consistently came in at right around 3.6, which is way under what you need to be safe, and adding more vinegar eventually made PH level plateau at right around 3.2, which begs the question of why we would ever pickle something in 100% vinegar, which plenty of mushroom pickles call for.</p>



<p>Anything preserved in 100% vinegar is far too strong for me. The lower amount of vinegar in conserve recipes gives you an advantage in that the mushrooms retain more of their flavor, making them more versatile.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image size-full wp-image-15758">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="1000" height="920" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201000%20920'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Chanterelle Mushroom Conserve" class="wp-image-15758" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5.jpg 1000w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-300x276.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-768x707.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-435x400.jpg 435w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1000" height="920" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5.jpg" alt="Chanterelle Mushroom Conserve" class="wp-image-15758" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5.jpg 1000w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-300x276.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-768x707.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-2-of-5-435x400.jpg 435w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">You can also store the conserve in a jar, just make sure everything is covered by liquid.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-the-end-all-mushroom-pickle-for-most-species-nbsp">The End-All Mushroom Pickle for most species&nbsp;</h2>



<p>I guarantee you, once you try this recipe, you may never want to simply pickle mushrooms again. I used hedgehog and chanterelle mushroom in the pictures here because they're probably my favorite for conserve but you could use a lot of different mushroom species, epecially if they're in the button stage.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image size-full wp-image-29299">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="835" height="1080" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20835%201080'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Hedgehog mushrooms or Hydnum umbillicatum" class="wp-image-29299" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5.jpg 835w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-768x993.jpg 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 835px) 100vw, 835px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="835" height="1080" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5.jpg" alt="Hedgehog mushrooms or Hydnum umbillicatum" class="wp-image-29299" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5.jpg 835w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Hedgehog-mushrooms-with-persillade-5-768x993.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 835px) 100vw, 835px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Hedgehog mushrooms are another good candidate.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<p>If it's a mushroom you can pick, it can probably be conserved, and wild mushroom blends are good too. One thing to know though, is that <a title="Ground Prune/Aborted Entoloma/Entoloma Abortivum" href="https://foragerchef.com/entoloma-abortivum-aborted-entoloma-mushroom/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="color: #ff0000;">a<span style="color: #ff0000;">borted entolomas</span></span> </a>and any species of <span style="color: #ff0000;"><a title="Prairie Caviar: Puffball Mushroom/Giant Puffball/Lycoperdons" href="https://foragerchef.com/puffball-mushrooms-aka-redneck-caviar/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="color: #ff0000;">puffball </span></a></span>I like to caramelize until lightly golden in oil before the vinegar and liquid is added, otherwise they just don't taste as good, a bit like some cousin of crumpled tofu.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image size-full wp-image-8919">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="900" height="600" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20900%20600'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="rainbow trout with chicken of the woods mushrooms" class="wp-image-8919" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10.jpg 900w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-600x400.jpg 600w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-680x453.jpg 680w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="900" height="600" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10.jpg" alt="rainbow trout with chicken of the woods mushrooms" class="wp-image-8919" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10.jpg 900w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-600x400.jpg 600w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/rainbow-trout-with-pickled-sulphur-shelf-mushrooms_-10-680x453.jpg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Conserve is a great garnish for entrees, pictured is chicken of the woods with rainbow trout.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<p>There's a couple things that are good to know about preserving mushrooms this way, and I would give the same advice for pickles. Here are some tricks I've learned after using this recipe for years. At one restaurant, I used to make this in 80lb batches, weekly-- I might know a thing or two about it.</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Only use young mushrooms for conserve and pickles, small tight buttons will yield the highest quality product. Larger, more mature mushrooms are better dried.</li>



<li>Don't go crazy with the flavoring ingredients. Adding a whole bunch of herbs, garlic and spices will make your mushroom conserve (or pickles for that matter) taste like medicine. Start with my tested proportions and get creative later.</li>
</ul>


<div class="wp-block-image wp-image-27735 size-full">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1200" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Morel mushrooms from Minnesota" class="wp-image-27735" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5.jpg 1200w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-300x300.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-400x400.jpg 400w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-150x150.jpg 150w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-768x768.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-500x500.jpg 500w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-360x360.jpg 360w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-720x720.jpg 720w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-180x180.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1200" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5.jpg" alt="Morel mushrooms from Minnesota" class="wp-image-27735" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5.jpg 1200w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-300x300.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-400x400.jpg 400w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-150x150.jpg 150w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-768x768.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-500x500.jpg 500w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-360x360.jpg 360w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-720x720.jpg 720w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Morels-2020-5-180x180.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">It might surprise you, but morels are good pickled too.</figcaption></figure>
</div>

<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="773" height="1000" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20773%201000'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Morel Mushrooms from Minnesota on a sheet tray " class="wp-image-39446" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10.jpg 773w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-768x994.jpg 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 773px) 100vw, 773px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="773" height="1000" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10.jpg" alt="Morel Mushrooms from Minnesota on a sheet tray " class="wp-image-39446" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10.jpg 773w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-232x300.jpg 232w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-309x400.jpg 309w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Morels-2021-10-768x994.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 773px) 100vw, 773px" /></noscript></figure>
</div>


<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-how-i-use-it-nbsp"><strong>How I Use It&nbsp;</strong></h3>



<p>This is how a lot of chefs preserve mushrooms en-masse, and, although they have a little acid to them, and they're in a container of liquid, it definitely doesn't mean that they're to be relegated to a bloody mary skewer or part of a pickle plate. <em>Oh hayll no</em>.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Like I mentioned, wet preservation like this is probably the best way to keep the texture of fresh mushrooms, salting comes in a close second, but then they need to be rinsed and soaked before hand. With mushroom conserve, all you do is pull them out of the jar and warm them up if you want. Easy money.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image wp-image-16011 size-full">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="1000" height="948" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201000%20948'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Baked chanterelle mushroom conserve with wild greens and melted brie" class="wp-image-16011" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6.jpg 1000w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-300x284.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-768x728.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-422x400.jpg 422w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1000" height="948" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6.jpg" alt="Baked chanterelle mushroom conserve with wild greens and melted brie" class="wp-image-16011" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6.jpg 1000w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-300x284.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-768x728.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Baked-chanterelle-conserve-with-wild-greens-and-melted-brie-3-of-6-422x400.jpg 422w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></noscript><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Warmed up with a slice of brie on top and served with a salad and lunch is served.</figcaption></figure>
</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-pro-tip-serve-them-warm-nbsp">Pro Tip: Serve them Warm&nbsp;</h2>



<p>Most of the time, I like to warm these up and add them to a dish, as a garnish to finish a plate, or as part of a warm salad, or appetizer. They can even be an appetizer in themselves.</p>



<p>Baked in a dish with a little liquid and topped with a slice of brie and melted under the broiler in an oven, they're ridiculously good spooned on toast, with a green salad on the side to cut the richness. I'm sure you can figure out plenty of things to do with them, if you don't end up eating them out of the jar standing in front of the fridge.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1200" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Chanterelle Mushroom Conserve" class="wp-image-15761" data-lazy-srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5.jpg 1200w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-300x300.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-400x400.jpg 400w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-150x150.jpg 150w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-768x768.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-500x500.jpg 500w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-360x360.jpg 360w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-720x720.jpg 720w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-180x180.jpg 180w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1200" src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5.jpg" alt="Chanterelle Mushroom Conserve" class="wp-image-15761" srcset="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5.jpg 1200w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-300x300.jpg 300w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-400x400.jpg 400w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-150x150.jpg 150w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-768x768.jpg 768w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-500x500.jpg 500w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-360x360.jpg 360w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-720x720.jpg 720w, https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Chanterelle-Mushroom-Conserve-5-of-5-180x180.jpg 180w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>
