	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-392218">
	<article id="article-comment-392218">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Amelia R Straub</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">August 21, 2025 at 2:38 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>I never seem to end up with enough liquid to feel safe with canning, so I typically end up putting them in the fridge anyway, but I often add the extra 4:1 ratio water and rice wine or white wine vinegar to top off + oil on top of each jar..<br />
 I prefer to do half pints so they're close to one meal or one potluck contribution worth.... I always have way too many mushrooms this time of year and my freezer is already full with morels and other delicious mushrooms, waaaaay more than I need  .... and I'm literally giving away mushrooms like zucchini at this point in the season, not even bothering selling anymore.  All my Chefs have what they need (If only they would hear me about squirreling them away for winter)....<br />
Forager Chef, you have my heart.  I've been foraging since I could walk, and I adore how you put such effort into preserving not only the food but the history and the culture behind it. Foraging has been in my family for many generations and is my greatest passion. I'm glad to find someone who values it as much as I do.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392218" data-commentid="392218" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392218" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Amelia R Straub" aria-label="Reply to Amelia R Straub">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-392219">
	<article id="article-comment-392219">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">August 21, 2025 at 9:56 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Thanks so much Amelia. If you come up short on liquid, try letting the mushrooms soak for a few minutes, there's actually old French recipes that call for chanterelles to be soaked before cooking, which actually makes sense for very thick buttons. If you're using a blend of mushrooms they can have different absorbtion rates. Either way I'm glad you've found a workaround that you're happy with, and I appreciate you sharing. Be well.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392219" data-commentid="392219" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392219" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even depth-2" id="comment-392319">
	<article id="article-comment-392319">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Hyperion Grey Solomon</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">August 31, 2025 at 3:23 pm</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Yeap, this happened to me too. Luckily it's a small batch and Im giving them as gifts. They did indeed soak up a lot of the liquid and are now no longer under the liquid line. I wonder how long these will keep? I did a 15 minute hotwater bath. </p>
<p>I'm glad the chef replied your comment, I know what to do differently next time 🙂 </p>
<p>I will soak them next time. Okay time for batch number two!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392319" data-commentid="392319" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392319" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Hyperion Grey Solomon" aria-label="Reply to Hyperion Grey Solomon">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-3" id="comment-392339">
	<article id="article-comment-392339">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">September 04, 2025 at 10:18 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Yes the varying levels of natural water content of mushrooms is a curve ball here, but easy to get around once you've made it a few times. Also a non-issue if the mushrooms will be held in the fridge, just press them under the liquid and top it off it needed.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392339" data-commentid="392339" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392339" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-392125">
	<article id="article-comment-392125">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Sarah Yarborough</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">August 11, 2025 at 11:41 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Love this recipe and highly recommend!! Sometimes I use rice wine vinegar to switch things up. </p>
<p>Question: with my last batch, I didn’t rinse the mushrooms enough so they didn’t have much water to give up. What’s best way to handle? Add more oil or some h2o while they’re wilting? Or a little more water when I add vinegar? I winged it and it worked out fine but curious what you recommend.  Thanks!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392125" data-commentid="392125" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392125" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Sarah Yarborough" aria-label="Reply to Sarah Yarborough">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-392130">
	<article id="article-comment-392130">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">August 11, 2025 at 4:26 pm</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Hi Sarah, there's a few things you can do. The proportions of the recipe as-is include plenty of vinegar, so if you want you can push the mushrooms under the liquid and top it off with oil to cover. You can also add a solution of water and vinegar to it, if you're using rice wine vinegar (which has a much lower acidity) I'd add a ratio of 1 part RWV to 4 parts water. You might need an extra 1/2 cup to top off a jar-not too much. How did you wing it?</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392130" data-commentid="392130" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392130" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-390110">
	<article id="article-comment-390110">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Kimberly</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">July 18, 2025 at 3:14 pm</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Thank you for sharing this recipe! Quick question: Would pressure canning instead of water bathing negatively affect the texture/flavor at all? I’d like to give a jar to my sister but whenever possible I prefer to pressure can food I’m giving away. I plan on using cinnabar chanterelles if that matters for this question. Thanks!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-390110" data-commentid="390110" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-390110" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Kimberly" aria-label="Reply to Kimberly">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-390224">
	<article id="article-comment-390224">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">July 19, 2025 at 6:59 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Pressure canning is fine.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-390224" data-commentid="390224" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-390224" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even depth-2" id="comment-392346">
	<article id="article-comment-392346">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Matt</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">September 05, 2025 at 11:42 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p><img class="wprm-comment-rating" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODdhAQABAPAAAP///wAAACwAAAAAAQABAEACAkQBADs=" data-lazy-src="https://foragerchef.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-recipe-maker/assets/icons/rating/stars-alt-5.svg" alt="5 stars" width="80" height="16" /><br />
God to know. Thanks Alan.</p>
<p>Also, I was curious how long they would last in jars if you didn’t refrigerate right away, and didn’t do the water can bath (i.e. just pickled them and put them in the jar and covered with liquid)? I was thinking of sending some as gifts, and figured mailing them after cooking would be best to get them there while fresh as possible. Just wanted to see how long you think they could last without refrigeration. Thanks again Alan!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392346" data-commentid="392346" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392346" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Matt" aria-label="Reply to Matt">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-3" id="comment-392349">
	<article id="article-comment-392349">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">September 05, 2025 at 12:08 pm</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>You bet. If you mail them make sure the jars are bubble wrapped. Ask my friend about mailing maple syrup 😆.</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-392349" data-commentid="392349" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-392349" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-380498">
	<article id="article-comment-380498">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Stefanía</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">December 14, 2024 at 4:23 am</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Hello:)</p>
<p>I was looking at this recipe whilst searching for what I can do with mushrooms I foraged after the frost had come and snow had settled. So I believe they have frozen and thawed already a couple of times before I picked them and I wanted to ask if it is still possible to use them for this recipe, or what I then got more curious about: whether it is still ok to thaw and then dry them?<br />
Or maybe the only thing one can do with them is eat them straight away or freeze them.</p>
<p>Thank you!</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-380498" data-commentid="380498" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-380498" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Stefanía" aria-label="Reply to Stefanía">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	<ul class="children">

	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alan-bergo bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-382362">
	<article id="article-comment-382362">

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<span class="comment-author-name">Alan Bergo</span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time">February 24, 2025 at 12:03 pm</time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Hi there, as mushrooms can get mushy after thawing and freezing it would be best to cook them (browning them will help them get flavor).</p>
		</div>

		<div class="comment-reply"><a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="#comment-382362" data-commentid="382362" data-postid="5843" data-belowelement="article-comment-382362" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Alan Bergo" aria-label="Reply to Alan Bergo">Reply</a></div>
		
	</article>
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->

	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-380093">
